'''Lateral violence''' is [[displacement (psychology)|displaced]] violence directed against one's peers rather than adversaries.  This construct is one way of explaining minority-on-minority violence in [[developed nations]].{{uncited|date=October 2018}}  Those experiencing and those committing lateral violence more likely to be involved in crime [[Race and crime in the United States|in the United States]], [[Race and crime in the United Kingdom|the United Kingdom]], and elsewhere.{{uncited|date=October 2018}}  In Australia and Canada, lateral violence is widely seen as an intergenerational learned pattern and major social problem in indigenous communities.<ref name="nwac">{{cite web |url=http://www.nwac.ca/sites/default/files/reports/AboriginalLateralViolence%20-%20web%20version.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811190226/http://www.nwac.ca/sites/default/files/reports/AboriginalLateralViolence%20-%20web%20version.pdf |archivedate=2014-08-11 |df= }}</ref>  In Australia surveys have reported that up to 95% of Aboriginal youth had witnessed lateral violence in the home, and that 95% of the bullying experienced by Aboriginals was perpetrated by other Aboriginals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creativespirits.info/aboriginalculture/people/bullying-lateral-violence|title=Bullying & lateral violence|first=Jens Korff, Creative|last=Spirits|website=Creative Spirits}}</ref>

{{quote|Lateral Violence occurs within marginalized groups where members strike out at each other as a result of being oppressed. The oppressed become the oppressors of themselves and each other. Common behaviours that prevent positive change from occurring include gossiping, bullying, finger-pointing, backstabbing and shunning.|Kweykway Consulting<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kweykway.ca/lateral-violence-in-first-nations-communities|title=Lateral Violence in First Nations Communities – Kwey Kway Consulting|website=www.kweykway.ca}}</ref>}}

Near-synonyms include '''horizontal violence''', '''intra-racial conflict''', and '''internalized colonialism'''

An example of inter-generational trauma would be the Corey and Cody Manyshots case involving two Aboriginal youth kidnapping and sexually assaulting a teen.<ref name="calgarysun.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.calgarysun.com/2014/11/17/calgary-police-charge-brothers-in-taradale-sex-attack-on-teen|title=Calgary police charge brothers in Taradale sex attack on teen|website=Calgary Sun}}</ref>  The father of the teens was involved in animal cruelty cases involving a [[Bichon Frise]] and elastic bands. Furthermore, the father threatened to attack reporters at his sons' trials.<ref name="calgarysun.com"/>  Corey Manyshots was on bail for defacing the Dashmesh Cultural Centre, a Sikh temple in [[Calgary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calgarysun.com/2014/11/24/calgary-brothers-accused-in-teens-sexual-assault-still-need-lawyers|title=Calgary brothers accused in teen's sexual assault still need lawyers|website=Calgary Sun}}</ref>  This interpretation through an intergenerational trauma perspective would understand that both Corey and Cody Manyshots were the subject of collective trauma from the colonial injustices passed down from generation to generation and have less of a responsibility for criminal acts and reprehensible behaviours.<ref>Bombay, Matheson, Anisman. ''Intergenerational Trauma: Convergence of Multiple Processes among First Nations peoples in Canada''. Journal de la santé autochtone, novembre 2009, p. 1.</ref> This interpretation is considered flawed by some and perpetuates violence among Aboriginals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/08/25/a-tragedy-that-doesnt-cry-for-an-inquiry|title=A tragedy that doesn't cry for an inquiry|website=Toronto Sun}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/put-native-women-on-the-agenda/article20144737/|title=Enough is enough: Time to address epidemic of violence against native women|last=Turpel-Lafond|first=Mary Ellen|date=21 August 2014|publisher=|via=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/analysis/aboriginal-women-fear-their-own-kind-the-most-285701831.html|title=Excuse me, there's a moose in the room|website=www.winnipegfreepress.com}}</ref> The Government of Canada commissioned a study in 2008 by the Minister of Health, it reported that although there were root causes such as the residential school system and loss of culture in Aboriginals which could lead to increases in propensities towards domestic abuse and violence, the aggravation factor in an overwhelming number of the cases involved drugs or alcohol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onwa.ca/upload/documents/aboriginal-women-and-family-violence.pdf |title=Aboriginal women and family violence |website=www.onwa.ca |format=PDF}}</ref>

Outside the racial context, the term is also used in explanation of [[workplace bullying]], though in that case the circumstances are much different. Some consider this an inappropriate definition.<ref name="nwac" />  [[Sexism in medicine]] has been identified as one environment in which lateral violence exists in the workplace and experienced by nurses who are men.<ref name=kron>{{cite journal|last1=Kronsberg|first1=Suzanne|last2=Bouret|first2=Josephine Rachel|last3=Brett|first3=Anne Liners|title=Lived experiences of male nurses: Dire consequences for the nursing profession|journal=Journal of Nursing Education and Practice|volume=8|issue=1|year=2017|page=46|issn=1925-4059|doi=10.5430/jnep.v8n1p46}}</ref><ref name = nurse>{{cite web|url=http://minoritynurse.com/male-nurses-confronting-stereotypes-and-discrimination-part-1-the-issues/|title=Male Nurses Confronting Stereotypes and Discrimination: Part 1, The Issues - Minority Nurse|website=minoritynurse.com|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2017/mar/01/why-so-few-male-nurses|title=Why are there so few male nurses?|first=Rachel|last=Williams|date=1 March 2017|publisher=|accessdate=4 September 2017|via=The Guardian}}</ref>

